{"cursor":"1931","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox single |\n| Name = The Best of Times | Cover = StyxBestOfTimes.jpg| Caption = | Artist =\n| Styx | from Album = Paradise Theatre | B-side = Lights | Released = 1981 |\n| Recorded = 1980 Genre = Progressive rock, pop rock Length = 4:17 Writer =\n| Dennis DeYoung Label = A$M Times'''\" (1981) | Last single = \"Borrowed\n| Time\" (1980) | This single = \"'The Best of Times'\" (1981) | Next\n| single = \"Too Much Time on My Hands\" (1981) |\n}}\n\n\"'The Best of Times'\" is the first single release from Styx's 1981 triple-\nplatinum album [[Paradise Theater (Styx album)|Paradise Theater]]. It reached #1\nin Canada on the ''RPM'' national singles chart, their second #1 in that country, http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_RPM_number-\none_singles_of_1981 and #3 on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100.\n\nThe basic melody line for \"The Best of Times\" is used in two other places on the\nalbum: As a bold greeting to the listener in \"A.D. 1928\", and a softer, more\nsubdued version for the farewell track, \"A.D. 1958\".\n\nThe song was featured in the 1999 movie [[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]], in\nwhich Adam Sandler's character is a Styx fan.\n\n\n\n\n{{succession box\n  | before = \"The Tide Is High\" by Blondie title = Canadian ''RPM'' number-one\n  | single years = March 7, 1981 (1 week) after = \"Woman\" by John Lennon\n}}\n","linknr":193,"url":"The_Best_of_Times_(song)","recorded":1375083220,"links":["/w/index.php?title=The_Best_of_Times_(song)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=The_Best_of_Times_(song)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls